### User:
How do you align a row of divs to the right using flex in css?  Show me an example.

### Response:


Sure, here's an example code snippet that demonstrates how to align a row of divs to the right using flexbox in CSS:
```css
.row {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
}
.col-md-6 {
  width: 50%;
  margin-left: -12px; /* Add negative left margin to center the div */
}
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .col-md-6 {
    width: 100%;
  }
}
```
In this example, we create a `.row` class that uses flexbox to align its child elements (`.col-md-6`) to the right. The `flex-direction: column;` property sets the direction of the flexbox as horizontal (column), and the `width: 50%;` property sets the width of each div to half of the parent element's width.
The negative left margin of `.col-md-6` centers the child elements within their parent row. The `@media (max-width: 768px)` rule is used for smaller screens, where we set the `width: 100%;` property to ensure that each div takes up the full width of its container.
I hope this helps! Let me know if you have any other questions.
